WEBVTT

00:01.001 --> 00:02.711
- No!
FRANK: Previously on Hardy Boys...

00:02.711 --> 00:04.296
[gasping]
ANGELA: Where's the eye?

00:04.296 --> 00:06.006
You know where it is, Frank.

00:06.006 --> 00:07.382
[high-pitched distortion]

00:07.382 --> 00:09.301
- No! [gasps]

00:09.301 --> 00:10.427
[insects chirping]

00:10.427 --> 00:12.638
- Keep it safe...

00:12.638 --> 00:14.348
- My name is Olivia Kowalski.

00:14.348 --> 00:16.558
FENTON: Your mother's Anya Kowalski,
the fortune teller.

00:16.558 --> 00:18.435
[gunfire]
[tires screech]

00:18.435 --> 00:20.771
OLIVIA: The Circle is vulnerable
for the first time in years.

00:20.771 --> 00:23.524
We have to move fast because
someone else is vying for control.

00:23.524 --> 00:25.275
It's the same person
who ordered Laura's death.

00:25.275 --> 00:26.944
[beeping]

00:26.944 --> 00:28.278
FRANK:
The tracker works. She got a signal.

00:28.278 --> 00:30.447
JOE: Why'd she let us go?
FRANK: Because it wasn't coming from me.

00:30.447 --> 00:31.240
- There's a bomb!

00:33.408 --> 00:34.701
LOLA:
No one was supposed to get hurt.

00:34.701 --> 00:36.703
BIFF: Mom! No! Mom!
CALLIE: Biff...

00:36.703 --> 00:39.581
RILEY: The girls confessed, but they're
claiming they never hurt the Gilroy kid.

00:39.581 --> 00:41.500
That someone paid them to do the bombing.

00:41.500 --> 00:44.503
Whoever it is wore a demon's mask,
used a voice changer.

00:44.503 --> 00:46.713
KRASSNER:
Let's, uh, keep this quiet.

00:46.713 --> 00:49.383
COX: I'm just going to leave you
my radio. If the day ever comes

00:49.383 --> 00:51.844
when you need the services
of a world-class thief,

00:51.844 --> 00:55.681
you can use it to get in touch when you're
ready to call in that favor. JB Cox.

00:56.223 --> 00:57.891
[rumbling]

00:57.891 --> 00:59.726
[fire crackling, hissing]

00:59.726 --> 01:02.020
[distortion]

01:02.020 --> 01:03.814
- Something worse is coming.

01:07.150 --> 01:09.570
♪ All at sea again ♪

01:10.153 --> 01:13.866
♪ And now my hurricanes ♪

01:13.866 --> 01:15.492
[muffled police radio chatter]

01:15.492 --> 01:18.954
♪ Have brought down this ocean rain ♪

01:20.247 --> 01:23.458
♪ To bathe with me again ♪

01:23.458 --> 01:25.961
[muffled paramedic chatter]

01:27.171 --> 01:29.923
♪ My ship's a sail ♪

01:29.923 --> 01:32.926
♪ Can you hear its tender frame ♪

01:34.595 --> 01:38.390
♪ Screaming from beneath the waves? ♪

01:39.308 --> 01:42.603
♪ Screaming from beneath the waves ♪

01:43.645 --> 01:47.024
♪ Screaming from beneath the waves ♪

01:48.150 --> 01:51.862
♪ Screaming from beneath your waves ♪

01:52.487 --> 01:55.115
♪ Screaming from beneath the... ♪

01:55.115 --> 01:58.952
♪ Waves... ♪

02:03.832 --> 02:07.127
♪ Screaming... ♪

02:07.878 --> 02:10.839
♪ From beneath the... ♪

02:10.839 --> 02:14.551
♪ Waves... ♪

02:18.222 --> 02:21.308
♪ All hands on deck at dawn ♪

02:22.434 --> 02:26.230
♪ Sailing to sadder shores ♪

02:27.648 --> 02:30.734
♪ Your port's in my heavy storm ♪

02:31.610 --> 02:36.698
♪ Harbors the blackest thoughts ♪

02:37.241 --> 02:39.201
JOE:
They were here today, I swear.

02:39.201 --> 02:40.994
FENTON:
Well, they're gone now.

02:43.038 --> 02:44.873
Hey, boys,

02:44.873 --> 02:48.335
why is it that Stratemeyer thinks
that you guys have The Eye, hm?

02:49.086 --> 02:51.380
Because we were all down here
when it was reforging,

02:51.380 --> 02:53.465
and they haven't come after me at all.

02:54.091 --> 02:56.885
- That's 'cause you're
a detective. We're just kids.

02:58.470 --> 02:59.721
- Shows what they know, huh?

03:01.557 --> 03:03.058
Let's do a quick sweep.

03:08.188 --> 03:09.898
- We should be telling him
the truth about The Eye.

03:10.858 --> 03:13.193
- Not now.
- Okay, well then when?

03:13.193 --> 03:16.446
- Alright, let's get out of here.
We should go to the cops, huh?

03:16.446 --> 03:18.407
- Uh, we can't do that.

03:18.407 --> 03:20.284
- It's not normally
my first instinct, either,

03:20.284 --> 03:22.828
but, uh, these Stratemeyer Global
guys, they're, uh,

03:22.828 --> 03:24.454
they're dangerous.
JOE: Yeah. It's just that

03:24.454 --> 03:27.040
I overheard Mayor Krassner
and Deputy Riley at the hospital.

03:27.040 --> 03:28.458
I don't know if we can trust them.

03:29.418 --> 03:32.212
- You think they're on the take?
- Well, I don't wanna risk it.

03:34.673 --> 03:37.426
- Wow. Then, I guess it's up to us, huh?

03:38.010 --> 03:39.636
- Really?
- Yeah.

03:40.137 --> 03:42.431
But, there is one thing that
I think you guys should know.

03:43.765 --> 03:45.767
And I don't think you're
going to like it very much.

03:48.103 --> 03:49.479
I'm working with your grandmother.

03:49.479 --> 03:52.482
♪

03:57.905 --> 04:00.157
We'll talk about it at home.

04:01.283 --> 04:05.037
- I didn't see that coming.
- Huh. Me neither.

04:06.079 --> 04:09.082
♪ theme song ♪

04:19.259 --> 04:21.011
FRANK: So, when you said
you were renovating the house

04:21.011 --> 04:22.513
in Dixon City--
- I lied.

04:23.597 --> 04:24.932
- Okay.
- You think Grandma's connected

04:24.932 --> 04:26.016
to Stratemeyer Global?

04:26.016 --> 04:27.434
- No, she's not just connected.

04:27.434 --> 04:29.645
She is Stratemeyer Global. Here.

04:32.356 --> 04:34.274
Follow the money.

04:34.274 --> 04:37.027
After George Estabrook's plane crashes,

04:37.027 --> 04:40.614
George Estabrook Enterprises
gets sold to Stratemeyer Global.

04:40.614 --> 04:42.616
Now, these guys, they're into
absolutely everything.

04:42.616 --> 04:44.910
Shipping, aerospace, technology, mining.

04:44.910 --> 04:47.246
You name it, they're there.
As far as the world is concerned,

04:47.246 --> 04:49.414
your grandmother just sold off
her father's company.

04:50.290 --> 04:53.710
Except that in reality,
all of this is her. The whole thing.

04:53.710 --> 04:56.255
And she's using Stratemeyer Global

04:56.255 --> 04:58.423
to control The Circle of The Eye

04:58.423 --> 05:00.884
without anybody knowing, from prison.

05:01.760 --> 05:03.679
- So, she can't send me
a birthday card from the slammer,

05:03.679 --> 05:06.014
but she can send hired goons after us?

05:06.014 --> 05:07.599
- Your grandmother didn't
have you kidnapped.

05:08.058 --> 05:09.268
- How do you know?

05:09.268 --> 05:11.687
- 'Cause you're family.
She'd never hurt you.

05:11.687 --> 05:14.106
[scoffs]
Whoever came after you guys,

05:14.106 --> 05:16.441
they're going rogue.
- Grandma told you all of this?

05:16.441 --> 05:19.236
- No. Grandma doesn't know that
I know because if she did,

05:19.236 --> 05:20.946
there's no way she would ask me to help.

05:20.946 --> 05:23.156
- And what exactly
are you helping her with?

05:23.156 --> 05:25.492
- Someone wants to put your
grandmother out of her company,

05:25.492 --> 05:26.994
out of The Circle,

05:26.994 --> 05:29.037
and she thinks it's the same
person who killed your mother.

05:30.455 --> 05:32.875
- How's that possible?
Stefan died in the tunnel collapse.

05:32.875 --> 05:33.876
- Yeah, how could he even--

05:33.876 --> 05:37.462
- Stefan ran your mother off the road,
but there's no way that guy acted alone.

05:38.172 --> 05:39.756
That guy didn't give orders.
He followed orders,

05:39.756 --> 05:42.092
so that's why I'm looking
into all of this stuff.

05:42.092 --> 05:43.802
Find out who's giving the orders now.

05:43.802 --> 05:46.180
- But it could still be Grandma.
FENTON: No, it's not.

05:46.180 --> 05:47.598
- You just said she was controlling--
- Guys!

05:47.598 --> 05:49.474
Your grandmother is a heck
of a lot of things,

05:49.474 --> 05:51.268
but she's not a killer.

05:51.268 --> 05:53.395
She wouldn't want to harm
her own daughter.

05:53.395 --> 05:56.190
Family, legacy, all this stuff
means the world to her.

05:57.191 --> 05:59.818
So as far as your mom's concerned,
we all want the same thing.

05:59.818 --> 06:01.695
We want the truth.

06:01.695 --> 06:03.113
Somebody's making a power play.

06:03.739 --> 06:06.116
We just gotta figure out
who that person is.

06:06.116 --> 06:08.744
JOE: Could be someone from
the original families, right?

06:09.328 --> 06:12.206
One of the, uh, Khans or the Nabokovs?
FENTON: Yeah, could be,

06:12.206 --> 06:14.041
but they're not talking.
They've all closed ranks.

06:14.041 --> 06:16.293
- Why? Are they scared?

06:16.293 --> 06:19.046
- No. I think they're waiting
to see how this all shakes out.

06:19.838 --> 06:21.006
- Could be Dean McFarlane.

06:21.006 --> 06:23.383
He led us to Grandma and The Circle
in the first place.

06:23.383 --> 06:25.427
He could have wanted her
out of the way, so he could take over.

06:25.427 --> 06:28.680
- Yeah, I thought so, too,
but turns out I was wrong.

06:28.680 --> 06:31.225
Dean McFarlane was poisoned for this.

06:31.934 --> 06:34.311
♪

06:34.311 --> 06:35.354
- No!

06:36.480 --> 06:38.482
- No... way.

06:38.482 --> 06:39.650
Who poisoned him?

06:40.275 --> 06:42.819
- Uh, someone named Olivia.

06:42.819 --> 06:44.738
She said that she is
Anya Kowalski's daughter.

06:45.614 --> 06:47.199
- What do you mean "she said"?
You talked to her?

06:47.199 --> 06:50.118
- Uh, yeah, I did. Um...

06:50.118 --> 06:53.330
Turns out that you guys weren't the only
ones to get kidnapped yesterday.

06:53.997 --> 06:56.291
Though I prefer to call it
a reverse interrogation.

06:56.291 --> 06:58.627
- Oh yeah? What'd you find out?
- Yeah.

07:00.212 --> 07:02.297
- That she claims...

07:02.297 --> 07:04.967
she knows who ordered your mother's death.

07:04.967 --> 07:06.134
♪

07:06.134 --> 07:09.638
She's willing to share that information
with me if I go to Dixon City.

07:09.638 --> 07:11.557
JOE:
What are you waiting for? Go see her!

07:11.557 --> 07:14.685
- No, no, guys. It's not that simple.
It's just-- It's not that simple.

07:14.685 --> 07:16.562
Olivia, she wants to destroy The Circle,

07:16.562 --> 07:18.480
but I don't know if I can trust her.

07:18.480 --> 07:20.691
I'm trying to find these people,
expose them,

07:20.691 --> 07:22.901
bring them to justice the right way,
And Olivia, she's trying to...

07:22.901 --> 07:24.486
JOE: She just wants
to kill everybody. I get it,

07:24.486 --> 07:26.738
but is that really such
a downside at this point?

07:26.738 --> 07:27.739
- Joe.

07:29.449 --> 07:31.076
I'm not going.

07:31.076 --> 07:33.412
- What are you talking about?
Dad, you have to go!

07:33.412 --> 07:34.788
- We're not letting you stay.

07:35.706 --> 07:38.709
- It didn't exactly work out all that well
when I left the last time, did it?

07:38.709 --> 07:40.752
- Dad, you said you wanted the truth.

07:42.546 --> 07:44.965
Alright, we want the truth, too.

07:44.965 --> 07:47.217
- If Olivia gets to this
mystery person first...

07:48.177 --> 07:49.678
then the truth dies with them.

07:49.678 --> 07:51.972
Could you really go your whole life

07:51.972 --> 07:55.017
not knowing who's responsible
for Mom's death?

07:55.017 --> 07:58.020
♪

07:58.562 --> 08:00.564
[birds chirping]

08:02.482 --> 08:04.860
- Alright. Here's the last box.

08:07.279 --> 08:09.156
[sighs] And there's one more thing.

08:09.656 --> 08:11.992
If Olivia is looking for this, um,

08:11.992 --> 08:14.870
it's probably best that
I don't have it on me, so...

08:14.870 --> 08:16.121
No one knows we have this.

08:16.121 --> 08:17.623
Keep it safe.

08:18.624 --> 08:20.167
- We will.

08:20.167 --> 08:22.169
- Okay. Oh, one more thing. Um...

08:23.420 --> 08:24.922
Here.

08:25.506 --> 08:28.967
This is the admin code to your
grandmother's alarm system

08:28.967 --> 08:31.720
in case you guys wanna
do any more snooping.

08:31.720 --> 08:33.555
This'll keep the armed guards
off your back.

08:33.555 --> 08:35.015
- Well, we could have
used this a lot sooner.

08:35.015 --> 08:36.850
- Well, you could have
told me a lot sooner.

08:36.850 --> 08:38.435
Hm?

08:38.435 --> 08:41.021
Come here. I-I don't really know
what I'm walking into,

08:41.021 --> 08:43.023
so, um, I'll be in touch when I can.

08:43.023 --> 08:45.442
[deep sigh]

08:47.277 --> 08:49.571
Love you, Joe. Love you, Frank.
- Love you, Dad.

08:49.571 --> 08:52.115
♪

08:52.115 --> 08:54.576
- Yeah, you're okay, too.
FENTON: Yeah, thank you. Thank you.

08:57.204 --> 08:59.206
- Why aren't we telling him
the truth about The Eye?

09:00.249 --> 09:01.834
- Well, if we tell him now, he won't go.

09:02.376 --> 09:04.169
We'll tell him when he gets back.

09:05.671 --> 09:07.172
♪

09:07.172 --> 09:10.342
[machines beeping]
[hospital chatter]

09:10.342 --> 09:13.220
- Is it connected? Your case and the kids?
- I'm gonna find out.

09:13.220 --> 09:15.556
I just want to make sure
you're good if I go.

09:17.432 --> 09:18.725
- I'll be fine.

09:19.643 --> 09:22.062
- I can stay. I can. I can stay.

09:22.062 --> 09:23.313
- Don't do that.

09:24.606 --> 09:26.817
You wouldn't be here
if you hadn't already made up your mind.

09:29.319 --> 09:32.114
Thank you for bringing the clothes.
- You're welcome.

09:32.114 --> 09:35.200
- I'm going to get Biff's things
and set up the spare room for her.

09:35.993 --> 09:38.495
School's canceled for the next
couple of days, so I can just...

09:39.454 --> 09:42.833
be here and be at the house. You can go.

09:43.834 --> 09:45.210
- Jesse's gonna be okay.

09:46.336 --> 09:47.629
She's a hero.

09:49.715 --> 09:51.842
- I don't need any more heroes.

09:53.635 --> 09:54.636
- Come here.

09:56.847 --> 09:58.265
[Trudy sighs]

09:59.808 --> 10:01.685
- Hey.
- Yeah?

10:03.520 --> 10:06.565
- Whoever did this to Jesse,
you need to get them.

10:06.565 --> 10:07.941
- Yeah.

10:08.483 --> 10:11.486
♪

10:12.946 --> 10:15.949
[beeping continues]

10:18.076 --> 10:20.078
[indistinct chatter, laughter]

10:21.747 --> 10:23.665
- Your dad seems happy.

10:23.665 --> 10:26.668
- Yup. New town, new romance.

10:26.668 --> 10:28.086
Like he's a whole new person.

10:29.338 --> 10:32.132
- You seem less happy...
- No, I-I'm fine.

10:32.132 --> 10:34.384
It's just he hasn't dated
anyone since the divorce,

10:34.384 --> 10:36.386
and she just kind of
came out of nowhere.

10:38.931 --> 10:40.349
- Coffees. [laughs]

10:40.766 --> 10:42.726
Looks like they're getting
Wilt's back in business.

10:42.726 --> 10:44.895
Just can't believe something like
this could happen in Bridgeport.

10:44.895 --> 10:46.438
- Well, you'd be surprised.

10:46.438 --> 10:48.398
- Well, I'm changing all my locks.

10:48.398 --> 10:50.275
Probably get
an alarm system for the house.

10:50.275 --> 10:52.361
The office, too. Better safe than sorry.

10:52.361 --> 10:54.154
- So, help me out here

10:54.154 --> 10:56.823
because I'm still trying
to wrap my head around all this.

10:56.823 --> 10:58.534
Why were you two chasing the bombers?

10:58.534 --> 11:00.869
- Well, technically, we were
only chasing one bomber.

11:00.869 --> 11:01.870
CHET:
Yeah.

11:01.870 --> 11:04.289
- Word on the street says
the Hardy boys were involved.

11:05.624 --> 11:07.501
- I didn't realize you knew them.

11:07.876 --> 11:09.962
- Only by reputation. They found

11:09.962 --> 11:12.089
that poor kid in the woods.
- Ah.

11:12.089 --> 11:13.465
I guess they fancy themselves

11:13.465 --> 11:15.676
some kind of detectives or something.
Like their dad.

11:15.676 --> 11:18.428
- Okay, but I still don't get it.
How did you know it was the girls?

11:19.179 --> 11:22.140
- It's... kind of hard to explain.
- Try me.

11:23.183 --> 11:26.103
- Well, long story short, we had
detention with Vanessa and Lola,

11:26.103 --> 11:27.980
and just kind of figured
it out from there.

11:27.980 --> 11:29.565
♪

11:29.565 --> 11:31.608
- What a relief.

11:31.608 --> 11:34.987
I was worried you two were involved
in something you shouldn't be.

11:34.987 --> 11:37.322
With dangerous people
you shouldn't be messing with.

11:40.075 --> 11:41.994
Who wants ice cream?
- Me.

11:41.994 --> 11:43.287
BELINDA: Yeah.
CHET: Cool.

11:43.287 --> 11:44.830
BRIAN:
Yeah.

11:44.830 --> 11:46.874
- Was there ever an incident
with Vanessa or Lola?

11:46.874 --> 11:48.125
[hammering]
- Never.

11:48.709 --> 11:50.586
- Anything that would have
caused them to retaliate?

11:50.586 --> 11:52.713
[police chatter]
- You think this is my fault?

11:52.713 --> 11:55.757
- Of course not.
I-I'm just trying to understand...

11:55.757 --> 11:59.094
Why your shop?
I love your shop. Everyone does.

11:59.469 --> 12:01.388
- Not everyone, apparently.

12:01.388 --> 12:04.016
- Is there anyone you can think of
who might have it out for you?

12:05.767 --> 12:07.227
- I don't know, Callie...

12:07.227 --> 12:09.605
Just doesn't make sense to me.

12:09.605 --> 12:11.857
I just want to rebuild and move on.

12:11.857 --> 12:14.026
- But this wasn't random, Wilt.

12:14.026 --> 12:15.819
It was carefully planned.

12:15.819 --> 12:17.070
Tom Elroy was framed.

12:17.070 --> 12:19.448
The bomb was hidden in the video game
days ahead of time.

12:19.448 --> 12:21.700
Whoever did this chose
your shop for a reason.

12:21.700 --> 12:24.786
- Well, we're lucky
that the damage wasn't worse.

12:24.786 --> 12:27.039
I mean, if I didn't close up
for the parade,

12:27.039 --> 12:29.416
it wouldn't just be
Jesse Hooper who was...

12:29.416 --> 12:31.502
[construction noise]

12:31.502 --> 12:35.005
Well, let's stop talking about my shop
like it's the only thing that matters.

12:35.672 --> 12:37.591
I'm not the only victim here.

12:37.591 --> 12:40.594
♪

12:42.721 --> 12:44.556
- The phone company's here.

12:47.976 --> 12:50.604
Hey, did the bomb take out
the phone lines?

12:50.604 --> 12:54.316
- Yeah, the alarm company techs are trying
to get their system up and running, too.

12:54.316 --> 12:55.526
[sweeping]

12:55.526 --> 12:58.278
Unfortunate for them,
being right next door.

12:58.278 --> 13:01.365
[indistinct chatter]

13:05.994 --> 13:08.455
- What do you got?

13:08.455 --> 13:11.083
- Wilt's shares a wall
with the alarm company.

13:11.083 --> 13:13.877
The same wall the video game was on.

13:13.877 --> 13:16.380
The blast destroyed
their monitoring systems.

13:18.465 --> 13:20.175
- Wilt's was never the target.

13:20.175 --> 13:22.052
It's just a decoy.

13:22.052 --> 13:24.054
- All this to take out
someone's alarm system.

13:24.054 --> 13:26.139
[distant siren]

13:26.139 --> 13:27.641
But whose?

13:27.641 --> 13:29.268
♪

13:33.981 --> 13:35.440
- Bring your pillow.
It might make you feel

13:35.440 --> 13:37.442
more at home at my place.

13:37.442 --> 13:38.485
- Right.

13:39.736 --> 13:42.573
- You know, I can't promise
that the pullout couch

13:42.573 --> 13:44.908
is going to be any more
comfortable than your own bed,

13:44.908 --> 13:47.411
but sure beats the chairs at the hospital.

13:48.412 --> 13:50.080
I'm going to go get some groceries later.

13:50.080 --> 13:51.582
Any special requests for dinner?

13:52.082 --> 13:53.709
- I don't care.

13:53.709 --> 13:55.085
♪

13:55.085 --> 13:56.670
- What about in the morning?

13:56.670 --> 13:58.881
Any favorite cereal or jam,

13:58.881 --> 14:00.966
juice--
- Just whatever, Trudy.

14:00.966 --> 14:02.176
I really don't care.

14:04.052 --> 14:06.722
- I heard the doctors talking.
They sounded really optimistic.

14:07.556 --> 14:08.849
- Can we just go?

14:11.518 --> 14:12.519
[sighs]

14:16.773 --> 14:18.859
[birds chirping]
CALLIE: Okay, so...

14:18.859 --> 14:20.360
the alarm system has a failsafe.

14:20.360 --> 14:22.362
If the power goes out,
the backup batteries kick in,

14:22.362 --> 14:24.448
but if the dedicated hub
is disrupted by, say,

14:24.448 --> 14:27.326
an explosion that takes out
the local lines, then, um, hang on.

14:27.326 --> 14:30.454
Then the digital communicator
needs to dial the central server

14:30.454 --> 14:33.165
to find a new feeder and connect
to an alternate monitoring station,

14:33.165 --> 14:34.708
leaving a 60-second window

14:34.708 --> 14:36.001
where all the contacts and sensors

14:36.001 --> 14:37.503
at the protected properties won't engage.

14:37.503 --> 14:39.588
- If you say so.
- What I'm saying is

14:39.588 --> 14:41.507
an intruder could get in,

14:41.507 --> 14:44.051
steal something, and get out
without anyone knowing.

14:44.051 --> 14:47.471
- Okay, so you think the bomb
was a distraction for, what, a robbery?

14:47.471 --> 14:48.680
- That's the working theory.

14:48.680 --> 14:50.766
- Okay, but why such an elaborate plan?

14:50.766 --> 14:53.060
I mean, like, why not just smash
and grab or cut the phone line?

14:53.060 --> 14:54.061
JOE:
Well, it's too obvious.

14:54.061 --> 14:56.104
A bomb at the monitoring station
takes out all the lines.

14:56.104 --> 14:57.648
- Yeah, this is the only way

14:57.648 --> 14:59.942
to obscure the location of the robbery.

14:59.942 --> 15:02.569
- The bombing caused
mass panic, pulled resources,

15:02.569 --> 15:04.613
and provided two patsies to take the fall.

15:04.613 --> 15:07.199
It's the perfect cover.
No one knows it happened.

15:07.199 --> 15:08.283
- Well, we do.

15:08.283 --> 15:09.910
- So, there's only one question left.

15:10.327 --> 15:11.453
Where was the robbery?

15:11.453 --> 15:13.455
- And what was stolen?
- And who did it?

15:13.455 --> 15:14.748
- Okay, three questions.

15:14.748 --> 15:15.832
- Do you remember the signal?

15:15.832 --> 15:17.835
- Four questions.
- What signal?

15:17.835 --> 15:19.545
- Five questions.
- Phil, would you please?

15:19.545 --> 15:20.712
- Was that a question?
JOE: Phil!

15:20.712 --> 15:23.298
Stratemeyer picked up a signal around
the same time as the bombing.

15:23.298 --> 15:25.968
At least within 60 seconds.
- A signal of what?

15:25.968 --> 15:28.428
- They have a device that tracks
the energy signature of The Eye.

15:29.763 --> 15:31.890
- So, you think The Eye's back in play?
FRANK: Maybe, or what if

15:31.890 --> 15:35.143
there's something else in town
that has the same energy signature?

15:35.143 --> 15:36.645
- How do you know it's not The Eye?

15:37.646 --> 15:39.273
- Call it a hunch.

15:39.273 --> 15:41.650
Look, I caught a glimpse of their tracker,

15:41.650 --> 15:44.570
and it had these coordinates.

15:48.448 --> 15:50.450
- Um...
[writing]

15:57.499 --> 15:59.793
- You memorized that?
- Yeah.

15:59.793 --> 16:01.295
You figure out these coordinates,

16:01.295 --> 16:02.921
we find out the location of the robbery.

16:02.921 --> 16:05.716
- Okay, that's great in theory,
but how are we gonna--

16:05.716 --> 16:07.426
- Ooh! Ooh! We can map it!

16:07.426 --> 16:09.261
I do cartography at
the Sea Cadets all the time.

16:09.261 --> 16:10.888
I'll go get my nautical maps
and my world atlas!

16:10.888 --> 16:12.097
- Can't we just use a globe?

16:12.097 --> 16:14.099
- Globe only gives us degrees.
We need minutes and seconds.

16:14.099 --> 16:15.225
I'll be right back!

16:15.225 --> 16:17.352
Or, alternatively, what we could do

16:17.352 --> 16:19.563
is this really cool method
where we figure out where we are

16:19.563 --> 16:21.023
and then work our way to the coordinates.

16:21.023 --> 16:22.566
Takes a lot longer
and it's way less accurate,

16:22.566 --> 16:24.985
but if you guys are up for the challenge,
we can use celestial navigation.

16:24.985 --> 16:26.820
Does anyone have
any star risings memorized?

16:26.820 --> 16:28.488
And this is the catch. Can't be the sun--

16:28.488 --> 16:29.740
[overlapping yelling]

16:29.740 --> 16:31.074
CHET: Go!
PHIL: Bye!

16:31.617 --> 16:34.494
[doorbell rings]
- Uh, I'll be right back, guys.

16:35.829 --> 16:37.915
[door shuts]
LUCY: Hey.

16:38.874 --> 16:40.334
Phil let me in. I hope that's okay.

16:40.334 --> 16:42.377
- Yeah, no, th-that's fine. It's cool.

16:42.377 --> 16:44.588
Is everything okay?
Did something happen to Dennis?

16:45.506 --> 16:47.508
- I just needed to get away
from the hospital for a bit.

16:49.218 --> 16:50.427
I thought maybe we could talk.

16:50.427 --> 16:51.803
- Oh.

16:52.304 --> 16:53.347
Right.

16:53.805 --> 16:55.182
- Do you wanna go for a bike ride?

16:55.599 --> 16:57.518
- Right now? No, I can't.

16:57.518 --> 16:59.436
I got to stay and help with...

17:00.854 --> 17:03.941
You kn-- Actually,
I've got some time.

17:04.399 --> 17:06.193
Where do you want to go?

17:06.193 --> 17:07.736
- Ever been to the lighthouse?

17:08.654 --> 17:10.906
- Uh, no.

17:10.906 --> 17:12.574
I've always wanted
to-to check it out, though.

17:12.574 --> 17:13.992
♪

17:13.992 --> 17:16.870
I-I'm gonna-- I'm gonna write
a note. I-I'll be right there.

17:26.129 --> 17:28.131
[puts down pen, rips paper]

17:33.387 --> 17:35.055
- Where are my maps, Tiffany?!

17:35.055 --> 17:37.057
TIFFANY:
Why would I move your stupid maps?

17:38.851 --> 17:42.020
- Here's that dumb phone book you wanted.
- Okay. Thank you.

17:42.020 --> 17:43.772
- Who do you even know
in Ducksworth anyway?

17:43.772 --> 17:45.440
- W-well, no one. It's for Biff.

17:46.108 --> 17:48.193
- She's that girl you like.
- What? No! I...

17:48.193 --> 17:49.444
- She's cute.

17:49.444 --> 17:51.572
Way too cute for you.
- Okay, just get outta my room.

17:51.572 --> 17:53.657
I need to find the maps.
Come on, let's go. Come on.

17:53.657 --> 17:54.825
- You're so weird, Philly.

17:55.492 --> 17:57.995
- The maps were behind the door, Tiffany!

17:57.995 --> 17:59.997
[grabs maps]

17:59.997 --> 18:01.498
Every second counts!

18:03.792 --> 18:06.795
♪ radio playing ♪

18:06.795 --> 18:08.213
CHET:
Hey...

18:08.672 --> 18:09.882
- Hey.

18:09.882 --> 18:12.968
- So, I was thinking...

18:12.968 --> 18:15.971
we should probably talk about that kiss.

18:17.055 --> 18:19.057
- Yeah, yeah, we should.

18:20.475 --> 18:23.478
- So, was it just adrenaline, or...

18:24.188 --> 18:27.399
was it something more?
- Oh, come on.

18:27.399 --> 18:30.527
Chet, you can't tell that I've liked you
since I first saw you in detention?

18:30.527 --> 18:33.238
- Okay, see, that's what I thought,
but then you mentioned Erica,

18:33.238 --> 18:35.782
and she showed up
out of nowhere, and I just...

18:35.782 --> 18:37.534
I don't know, I thought,
maybe you weren't into guys.

18:37.534 --> 18:38.744
- I like both.

18:39.369 --> 18:42.539
- You good with that?
- Yeah, I'm good.

18:42.539 --> 18:44.082
It's good to know.

18:44.875 --> 18:47.127
- Do you want to kiss again?

18:50.339 --> 18:51.965
- [laughs] I do.

18:52.508 --> 18:55.886
- Okay! Let's figure out
who got robbed. Move.

18:55.886 --> 18:57.554
[radio stops]
Move, move, move. Let's go. Come on.

18:57.554 --> 18:58.889
Come on. Today.

19:01.183 --> 19:05.020
So first, we plot the degrees,
which take us here.

19:05.020 --> 19:06.730
[crinkling]

19:06.730 --> 19:08.815
And then we plot the minutes,

19:08.815 --> 19:10.108
which take us down to Bridgeport...

19:10.859 --> 19:14.696
CALLIE: Here.
- ...which takes us here. And then,

19:14.696 --> 19:16.865
we zoom in by doing a little bit of math

19:16.865 --> 19:19.284
by dividing the seconds by six,

19:19.284 --> 19:21.495
which brings us down to the tenths.
CALLIE: Do you need a calculator?

19:21.495 --> 19:23.038
- Uh, no, I got it. Math's my thing.

19:23.038 --> 19:25.457
And then we jump from
the nautical map to the town map

19:25.457 --> 19:28.460
by matching the shorelines,
and then scaling accordingly.

19:28.460 --> 19:30.796
And if we do that, it takes us...

19:30.796 --> 19:32.714
right here.
That's where the signal came from.

19:32.714 --> 19:35.717
♪

19:35.717 --> 19:37.219
- That's my grandma's house.

19:41.807 --> 19:44.810
[street noise, car honks]

19:44.810 --> 19:47.813
♪

19:47.813 --> 19:50.816
[indistinct chatter]

19:52.067 --> 19:54.361
- Can I help you, sir?
- No, I'm good, thanks.

19:55.737 --> 19:57.239
- Okay then.

20:03.829 --> 20:05.831
[door creaks shut]

20:14.506 --> 20:16.550
♪

20:24.808 --> 20:26.685
[rattles door knob]

20:26.685 --> 20:27.686
[sighs]

20:28.854 --> 20:31.857
[passing siren]

20:36.195 --> 20:38.488
[hissing]

20:38.488 --> 20:39.489
[grunts]

20:39.489 --> 20:42.492
[coughing]

20:43.327 --> 20:46.455
[grunting, gasping]

20:46.455 --> 20:49.124
♪

20:51.919 --> 20:54.922
[panting]

20:56.006 --> 20:58.717
- I'm so glad you decided
to join me, Fenton.

20:59.384 --> 21:01.929
You're going to be very useful.

21:01.929 --> 21:04.806
But for now, just rest.

21:05.307 --> 21:07.809
[gasping]

21:07.809 --> 21:09.311
[sighs]

21:10.938 --> 21:13.941
[waves lapping]
[gulls cawing]

21:15.567 --> 21:17.653
LUCY: Can't believe
you haven't been here yet.

21:17.653 --> 21:20.030
Ah, you know. I'm a... busy guy.

21:21.156 --> 21:22.908
LUCY:
So, what do you think?

21:22.908 --> 21:25.619
Worth the wait?
- Definitely. Yeah.

21:25.619 --> 21:28.622
[quiet splashing]

21:28.622 --> 21:31.208
♪

21:31.583 --> 21:33.877
- Hey, can I ask you something?

21:33.877 --> 21:35.254
- Sure.

21:36.338 --> 21:38.173
- You and Dennis...

21:38.173 --> 21:40.175
don't really makes sense to me.

21:40.175 --> 21:42.010
[nervous laugh]

21:42.010 --> 21:43.387
- That's not a question.

21:43.804 --> 21:46.890
- I mean, you're so... you know, and...

21:46.890 --> 21:48.642
He's just a little--
- Kind of a jerk?

21:48.642 --> 21:49.893
JOE:
Yeah.

21:49.893 --> 21:51.854
- [scoffs] And you're not?

21:52.688 --> 21:53.856
- You think I'm a jerk?

21:54.314 --> 21:55.607
[both laugh quietly]

21:56.191 --> 21:58.360
Yeah, I guess I'm a bit
of a jerk sometimes.

21:58.944 --> 22:01.029
- Like a part-time jerk.

22:01.655 --> 22:03.448
[distant thunder]

22:07.119 --> 22:08.537
JOE:
You know...

22:09.288 --> 22:12.749
you can't just keep pretending
to be his girlfriend.

22:14.209 --> 22:15.252
- No.

22:16.795 --> 22:18.463
- What happens when he gets better?

22:20.048 --> 22:22.217
- I'll have to figure that out.

22:22.217 --> 22:24.761
[honk, vehicle approaching]

22:27.055 --> 22:29.141
♪

22:29.141 --> 22:30.767
- Looks like we got a new lead.

22:30.767 --> 22:33.312
[truck shifts into park]
You wanna join us?

22:33.312 --> 22:35.397
[engine stops]
- No.

22:35.397 --> 22:38.150
I can't really handle
other people right now.

22:38.150 --> 22:40.903
I think I'm going to stay
and watch the storm roll in.

22:41.653 --> 22:42.863
Do you want to stay with me?

22:43.739 --> 22:44.990
- I do.

22:46.408 --> 22:49.244
[sighs] But, I shouldn't.

22:53.290 --> 22:54.917
- Hey, Joe?

22:54.917 --> 22:56.752
[truck door shuts]
Be careful.

22:57.294 --> 22:58.295
[sighs]

23:01.173 --> 23:04.176
[insects chirping]

23:04.176 --> 23:06.762
[alarm beeping]

23:06.762 --> 23:10.140
[buttons beeping, alarm stops]

23:10.140 --> 23:12.142
- So, no security?
- No, we're good.

23:12.809 --> 23:15.812
♪

23:18.440 --> 23:21.360
CHET: Okay, so where do we start?
- Duh. The secret room, obviously,

23:21.360 --> 23:22.861
- No, there's no point.

23:24.154 --> 23:25.614
- That room's armed with a kill switch.

23:25.614 --> 23:27.741
If somebody tried to break in,
it would have exploded.

23:28.784 --> 23:31.286
Whatever was stolen was stolen
from somewhere else in the house.

23:31.286 --> 23:34.456
- Okay, back up. There's a secret room
armed with a kill switch?

23:34.456 --> 23:36.124
- Yeah, it's like a whole thing.

23:36.124 --> 23:39.461
George Estabrook was a tad eccentric.
- Just a tad.

23:39.461 --> 23:42.047
- Okay I don't want to rain on
our little search party,

23:42.047 --> 23:44.383
but how are we going to figure out
what was stolen if it was stolen?

23:44.383 --> 23:46.385
- I'll figure it out.
- How?

23:48.679 --> 23:51.640
- Uh, well, we search
for signs of theft, right?

23:51.640 --> 23:54.184
You know, dust outlines,
tilted picture frames...

23:54.184 --> 23:56.895
- A window that's been jimmied open?
- Exactly.

23:56.895 --> 23:59.398
- No. No, no, no,
this window's been jimmied open.

24:02.067 --> 24:04.111
[birds chirping outside]

24:04.111 --> 24:05.946
This must have been the point of entry.

24:07.614 --> 24:10.117
[high-pitched ringing, creaking, thud]

24:10.117 --> 24:11.869
The intruder couldn't
re-lock it behind him.

24:11.869 --> 24:13.328
- Sixty seconds isn't a long time.

24:13.328 --> 24:15.956
They must've known where they were going.
- And exactly what they were stealing.

24:15.956 --> 24:17.875
Whatever it was had to be close.

24:17.875 --> 24:20.210
- Let's split up.
PHIL: Okay.

24:20.210 --> 24:23.213
♪

24:28.886 --> 24:30.220
CHET:
Hey, check this out.

24:30.220 --> 24:32.848
[rummaging, searching]

24:34.391 --> 24:35.601
[tinnitus sound, scrape]

24:40.063 --> 24:42.316
[ringing, clink]

24:42.316 --> 24:44.443
- There's a crystal missing.

24:44.443 --> 24:46.737
[static, distortion]

24:46.737 --> 24:49.323
[clinking, thud, scraping]

24:52.326 --> 24:54.244
[panting]

24:54.244 --> 24:56.079
- What's wrong with you?

24:56.079 --> 24:57.080
- It's nothing.

24:58.332 --> 25:00.334
- Ten bucks says it's something.

25:00.334 --> 25:01.793
[door creaks open]

25:02.711 --> 25:05.005
- [loud whisper]: Hide! Secret room!
Now! Go! Get the door!

25:06.048 --> 25:07.841
[doors creaking]

25:07.841 --> 25:09.218
Go, go, go, go, go, go, go.

25:10.636 --> 25:11.970
[creaking]

25:14.681 --> 25:17.684
[tracker beeping]

25:20.854 --> 25:22.648
♪

25:24.650 --> 25:27.110
- [whispers]:
It's that guy Mack from Stratemeyer.

25:27.110 --> 25:28.237
[tracker beeping]

25:28.237 --> 25:29.571
He's got the tracker.

25:29.571 --> 25:32.366
♪

25:32.366 --> 25:35.202
[beeping continues]

25:35.619 --> 25:37.287
- [whispers]: What's he tracking?

25:37.287 --> 25:39.665
- That was the lab.
Results are finally in

25:39.665 --> 25:41.625
on the hunk of rock
we found in the chamber.

25:41.625 --> 25:44.294
[beeping continues]
MACK: Let me guess.

25:45.629 --> 25:47.756
- Inconclusive.
- No.

25:47.756 --> 25:48.882
The relic's real.

25:48.882 --> 25:50.425
MACK:
That doesn't add up.

25:50.425 --> 25:52.135
If it really is The Eye,
where's the power?

25:52.803 --> 25:54.471
- Million-dollar question.

25:54.471 --> 25:57.140
Want to hear the craziest thing?
It's alien.

25:57.683 --> 25:59.810
- I knew it. I told you it was aliens.

26:00.477 --> 26:02.980
- Not little green men, idiot! Alien.

26:02.980 --> 26:05.065
Foreign. Other. Apparently,

26:05.065 --> 26:08.527
the relic's made of
unfamiliar unidentified elements

26:08.527 --> 26:09.862
not naturally found on Earth.

26:10.445 --> 26:11.697
- So, what do we do with the relic?

26:12.614 --> 26:15.659
- We lock it in the vault
until R&D lets us know

26:15.659 --> 26:18.704
where the hell it came from,
and where its power went.

26:18.704 --> 26:21.707
♪

26:21.707 --> 26:23.750
[beeping continues]

26:23.750 --> 26:24.918
Any luck on the signal?

26:24.918 --> 26:26.545
MACK: No.

26:26.545 --> 26:29.464
Same coordinates as yesterday.
There's nothing here.

26:30.048 --> 26:31.967
- The tracker can't read elevation.

26:31.967 --> 26:33.969
You take upstairs. I'll take down.

26:33.969 --> 26:36.972
[beeping continues]

26:37.890 --> 26:40.225
- We can't risk them finding us.

26:40.225 --> 26:42.644
We gotta go.
- The window.

26:44.104 --> 26:45.314
FRANK:
Go, go, go, go.

26:45.314 --> 26:47.191
♪

26:48.192 --> 26:49.902
[window opens]
Careful, careful.

26:49.902 --> 26:51.445
[creak]

26:56.283 --> 26:58.285
Phil, what are you doing?
- Leave no trace.

26:58.869 --> 27:00.913
ANGELA:
Hey, Mack! Downstairs is clear,

27:00.913 --> 27:02.873
but I wanna check
one more thing before we go.

27:02.873 --> 27:05.667
[panting]

27:05.667 --> 27:07.461
- We gotta help him.

27:07.461 --> 27:08.962
- You guys make a run
for the vehicles, okay?

27:08.962 --> 27:10.380
We'll pull them the other way.
- How?

27:10.380 --> 27:13.175
- Just trust me, okay? Go.
- Okay, we'll meet you at the attic.

27:13.175 --> 27:15.177
♪

27:21.683 --> 27:23.602
- I know someone's in here.

27:25.103 --> 27:27.231
If you think I'm bluffing, think again.

27:28.273 --> 27:30.442
You have until the count of five
to come out and talk.

27:30.442 --> 27:32.986
And if I get to six,
there'll be less talking.

27:34.321 --> 27:35.614
One...

27:35.614 --> 27:37.241
Two...

27:37.241 --> 27:39.201
Three, four, five.
- Okay, okay. You got me.

27:41.161 --> 27:42.788
But out of the two of us,

27:42.788 --> 27:45.165
I'm the only one
that's allowed to be here.

27:45.165 --> 27:47.584
This is private property, madam.

27:47.584 --> 27:50.921
Are you with the alarm company?
- Do I look like a rent-a-cop?

27:50.921 --> 27:53.674
- You look like you're trespassing.

27:53.674 --> 27:56.426
My name is Charles Estabrook V.

27:56.426 --> 27:58.512
I'm Gloria Estabrooks' great-nephew,

27:58.512 --> 27:59.638
on the mother's side.

27:59.638 --> 28:01.682
Now, may I ask you again?

28:01.682 --> 28:03.684
♪

28:03.684 --> 28:06.353
What, pray tell, are you doing
in my great aunty's house?

28:07.729 --> 28:09.106
- Your name is Philip Cohen.

28:09.106 --> 28:11.733
You live at 25 Carmel Road
with your mother

28:11.733 --> 28:13.902
and your father and four older sisters

28:13.902 --> 28:16.363
and your English cocker spaniel
named Chipper.

28:17.322 --> 28:20.450
So what, pray tell,

28:20.450 --> 28:22.661
are you doing here, Philip?

28:24.413 --> 28:26.874
- Okay. Here goes nothing.

28:28.500 --> 28:29.960
♪

28:29.960 --> 28:30.794
[groans]

28:30.794 --> 28:33.088
[distortion]

28:33.088 --> 28:34.089
[gasps]

28:39.928 --> 28:41.138
- [distorted]: Did it work, Frank?

28:41.138 --> 28:43.140
Frank?
[gasping]

28:43.140 --> 28:44.183
Frank, did it work?

28:45.142 --> 28:46.643
- Yeah. Go.

28:48.103 --> 28:50.606
- Angela, we got a hit outside the house.
[beeping]

28:52.733 --> 28:55.736
[beeping gets faster]

28:55.736 --> 28:58.739
[panting, brush breaking]

28:59.531 --> 29:02.534
♪

29:04.119 --> 29:07.122
[panting]

29:11.043 --> 29:14.046
[gulls cawing]

29:15.130 --> 29:18.050
[thunder rumbling]

29:18.050 --> 29:20.552
[leaves rustling]

29:20.552 --> 29:23.013
JOE: They won't be far behind.
Try and stay out of sight.

29:23.013 --> 29:24.348
[thunder]

29:26.266 --> 29:27.309
[thunder]

29:29.228 --> 29:31.271
- I see it!

29:31.271 --> 29:32.773
At the bottom of the fulgurite.

29:34.066 --> 29:36.109
[panting]

29:36.109 --> 29:37.736
♪

29:37.736 --> 29:41.114
Just where The Eye showed me it would be.

29:42.699 --> 29:46.453
[sighs] The question is was
the Flash Stone formed by the lightning,

29:46.453 --> 29:49.831
o-or was it attracting lightning
to this beach all this time?

29:50.832 --> 29:53.418
[heavy breathing]

29:58.340 --> 30:00.342
[panting]

30:05.597 --> 30:07.599
CHAUFFEUR:
Mr. Estabrook, what is it, sir?

30:10.060 --> 30:12.437
JOE: Frank? Frank!
[thunder]

30:12.437 --> 30:13.647
What did you see?

30:14.106 --> 30:16.149
- I don't know.
[thunder]

30:16.149 --> 30:18.735
It was different this time
- Okay, explain on the way. We gotta go.

30:18.735 --> 30:20.404
[explosion]

30:20.404 --> 30:22.990
[rocks raining down]

30:22.990 --> 30:26.034
[tracker beeping]

30:26.034 --> 30:27.828
MACK:
Are you seeing this?

30:28.412 --> 30:29.913
- Frank never had The Eye.

30:31.665 --> 30:33.166
He is The Eye.

30:35.002 --> 30:37.087
- This is above my pay grade.

30:37.087 --> 30:38.338
We got to tell the boss.

30:38.964 --> 30:41.633
ANGELA: You're right.
This is a real game changer.

30:42.926 --> 30:45.179
[grunts]

30:45.179 --> 30:47.139
But we're not telling anyone.

30:49.141 --> 30:52.144
♪

30:52.144 --> 30:55.022
[high-pitched ringing]
[muffled groaning]

30:55.022 --> 30:58.483
[muffled coughing]

30:59.151 --> 31:02.154
[muffled groaning, sighing]

31:02.154 --> 31:05.157
[muffled panting]

31:06.491 --> 31:08.493
- [muffled]:
Did we just get struck by lightning?

31:08.493 --> 31:10.329
[gull cawing]

31:10.329 --> 31:11.830
- [less muffled]: No, it hit the sand.

31:13.081 --> 31:16.084
[muffled sigh, grunting]
[waves washing ashore]

31:16.084 --> 31:19.087
[muffled panting]

31:19.087 --> 31:22.090
[ringing fades out]
[panting]

31:27.221 --> 31:28.222
- Ah!

31:28.222 --> 31:29.640
♪

31:29.640 --> 31:32.643
[gulls cawing]
[waves washing ashore]

31:34.436 --> 31:35.938
What is it?

31:38.106 --> 31:40.317
- We'll figure it out at home.

31:40.317 --> 31:41.818
Let's get out of here.

31:47.074 --> 31:48.867
♪

31:48.867 --> 31:50.285
PHIL:
It's fulgurite.

31:50.285 --> 31:51.745
The beach is known for it.

31:51.745 --> 31:53.789
I did a project one year,
so it's kind of baked into my head.

31:53.789 --> 31:56.375
See, sand melts at 1,800 degrees,

31:56.375 --> 31:59.086
but lightning is 30,000 degrees.
So, when the lightning hits the sand,

31:59.086 --> 32:01.505
the silicon melts and fuses
together while it's cooling.

32:01.505 --> 32:03.340
And this is called lightning glass,

32:03.340 --> 32:05.050
but you can't confuse it
with Flash Stones because--

32:05.050 --> 32:07.010
- Okay, Phil, we get it.
We don't need the whole report.

32:07.010 --> 32:08.595
- Wait, what'd you say? What stone?

32:08.595 --> 32:10.639
- Flash Stones. They're a local legend.

32:10.639 --> 32:12.140
Some New Age weirdos think they contain

32:12.140 --> 32:14.434
high-vibrational energy,
but it doesn't exist.

32:14.434 --> 32:16.728
- No, it does.
George wrote about it in his journal.

32:16.728 --> 32:18.605
He pulled it out of the ground
at the beach. I saw him.

32:18.605 --> 32:20.065
♪

32:20.065 --> 32:22.568
- What are you talking about?
- You mean George Estabrook?

32:24.319 --> 32:26.029
- Sorry. When did you see this?

32:26.822 --> 32:28.198
- In the journal.

32:28.198 --> 32:31.201
Saw it-- Y-you saw it George's journal.
Right, Frank?

32:32.536 --> 32:33.537
- No.

32:34.830 --> 32:36.707
Saw it in a vision.

32:36.707 --> 32:39.001
There's something I didn't
tell you about last fall.

32:39.710 --> 32:42.588
I didn't just figure out that
Stefan ran my mom off the road.

32:42.588 --> 32:45.591
I had to piece it together
with clues from The Eye.

32:47.259 --> 32:49.887
When I touched the relic,
there was all this light and energy.

32:49.887 --> 32:52.890
It was like The Eye got a hold
of me and it transported me...

32:52.890 --> 32:54.641
- Frank.
- It's okay.

32:55.267 --> 32:59.062
It transported me to
the last day my mom was alive.

33:04.735 --> 33:07.112
I saw her and Gloria fighting.

33:07.112 --> 33:09.990
It was like it was real, only...

33:09.990 --> 33:12.659
it wasn't because they couldn't see me.

33:12.659 --> 33:16.038
It was like my spirit or my consciousness.
I don't know.

33:17.748 --> 33:20.709
But then I woke up,
and the tunnel collapsed.

33:20.709 --> 33:22.377
The Eye was gone. It was over.

33:22.377 --> 33:24.713
- Yeah, a-a-and it stayed over.
It was all done

33:24.713 --> 33:27.216
and over--
- Until Dennis went missing.

33:28.759 --> 33:30.761
And then the visions started again.

33:32.137 --> 33:33.639
The energy stayed with me.

33:36.225 --> 33:38.227
I have the power of The Eye.

33:38.227 --> 33:41.271
♪

33:42.397 --> 33:43.857
- You owe me 10 bucks.

33:44.775 --> 33:45.817
- Yeah.

33:46.235 --> 33:48.946
- So, you've been having visions
this whole time.

33:48.946 --> 33:50.322
That's how you've been solving the case?

33:51.740 --> 33:53.534
- Yeah.
- All those hunches,

33:53.534 --> 33:55.744
all the lucky guesses, it was all...

33:57.246 --> 34:00.374
magic.
- Okay, hang on. It wasn't all magic.

34:00.374 --> 34:02.751
There was still
s-some classic sleuthing in there,

34:02.751 --> 34:03.919
especially on my part.

34:03.919 --> 34:06.713
- That is true.
We did have to connect the dots.

34:08.173 --> 34:10.384
But, yeah, it was mostly visions.

34:10.843 --> 34:12.761
Except today was different. You know,

34:12.761 --> 34:15.472
when I saw George on the beach,
it was like a real event.

34:15.472 --> 34:18.350
It's like I was actually there 'cause...

34:19.560 --> 34:20.686
George saw me.

34:22.104 --> 34:23.981
- Wait, what? Are you sure?

34:23.981 --> 34:25.190
- Maybe you imagined it.

34:25.190 --> 34:26.650
- Maybe the lightning did hit you.

34:26.650 --> 34:29.528
- No, guys, he looked at me.

34:29.528 --> 34:31.113
From the past!

34:31.113 --> 34:33.198
- That-that's impossible.
FRANK: Is it, Phil?

34:33.198 --> 34:34.575
Given everything that I've just said,

34:34.575 --> 34:36.827
seeing through time, that's where
we're going to draw a line?

34:38.161 --> 34:41.164
[giggling]

34:41.164 --> 34:44.168
[all laughing]

34:44.168 --> 34:47.171
♪

34:49.089 --> 34:50.632
PHIL:
Wait, wait, wait, wait, wait.

34:50.632 --> 34:53.010
How bad is it that Angela
knows my name and where I live?

34:53.010 --> 34:55.470
- It's bad.
[laughter]

34:55.470 --> 34:58.056
- No, no. Scale of one to 10?
- Twenty.

34:58.056 --> 35:00.976
PHIL: No, I-I'm being serious.
[laughter]

35:00.976 --> 35:02.394
FRANK:
Relax, Phil.

35:02.394 --> 35:04.396
If she was gonna hurt us,
she would have done it already.

35:04.396 --> 35:06.773
- It's late. I, uh, should go.

35:07.524 --> 35:09.484
- I'll drive you home.

35:11.528 --> 35:12.529
[Callie sighs]

35:13.655 --> 35:15.157
- We need to talk.

35:19.870 --> 35:20.871
[door creaks, shuts]

35:20.871 --> 35:23.248
- We should've talked
about telling everyone.

35:23.248 --> 35:25.292
- It was getting too hard
to keep it a secret.

35:25.292 --> 35:26.919
- You could have told Dad!

35:26.919 --> 35:28.378
He could have helped!
- He is helping.

35:28.378 --> 35:30.047
He's working his side of the case.
We're working ours.

35:31.131 --> 35:33.550
It's better this way, Joe.
It's not just you and me alone in this.

35:33.550 --> 35:35.886
We have our friends now.
- Well, what if someone slips up?

35:35.886 --> 35:37.888
What if Stratemeyer finds out?
Who knows what they'll do to you?

35:37.888 --> 35:40.015
- I don't think we need to worry about.
- Oh yeah?

35:40.015 --> 35:41.266
Did The Eye tell you that?

35:42.017 --> 35:44.061
- If they hurt me,
they risk damaging the power.

35:44.061 --> 35:45.812
If they kill me, it could be gone forever.

35:45.812 --> 35:48.440
- What if they send a team
of-of morally corrupt scientists

35:48.440 --> 35:51.151
who cart you off in some quarantine tent
like an extraterrestrial?

35:51.151 --> 35:52.819
- I don't think that's gonna happen.

35:52.819 --> 35:55.531
- You told me to keep you in check.
You said you'd listen to me!

35:55.531 --> 35:56.990
- We would've come to the same conclusion.

35:56.990 --> 35:58.116
- We're supposed to be
doing this together!

35:58.116 --> 36:00.369
- We are, Joe! Just trust me!

36:00.369 --> 36:01.745
♪

36:01.745 --> 36:03.205
The Eye will lead us to the crystal!

36:03.205 --> 36:05.916
The crystal will lead us to that
shadow man for my vision!

36:05.916 --> 36:07.543
- We didn't need The Eye last year.

36:08.919 --> 36:11.421
Maybe we don't need it at all now.

36:11.421 --> 36:14.049
L-look, if we got rid of the power--
- No!

36:15.551 --> 36:17.553
We need it. We'd be lost without it.

36:20.722 --> 36:21.723
[door slams]

36:24.893 --> 36:26.311
[sighs]

36:26.311 --> 36:28.981
[shuts car door]
[starts engine]

36:28.981 --> 36:30.524
- Is everything okay with Joe?

36:30.524 --> 36:32.442
- Yeah, it's fine. He's just worried.

36:32.442 --> 36:34.236
♪ radio playing ♪

36:34.236 --> 36:36.613
I'm fine. You know,

36:36.613 --> 36:39.324
I've been dealing with this for a while.
I've got it under control.

36:39.324 --> 36:41.869
♪ Wicked One by Velvet Moon ♪

36:41.869 --> 36:43.120
- Okay.

36:43.579 --> 36:45.998
[laughs]
- You were amazing today, by the way.

36:45.998 --> 36:48.792
All the stuff you figured out
about the alarm company.

36:48.792 --> 36:50.502
- Well, what can I say? I'm a genius,

36:50.502 --> 36:54.089
and I get bonus points for doing it
without any mystical, magical powers.

36:54.923 --> 36:56.925
- Touché.
[laughs]

36:57.426 --> 36:59.428
- You know...

36:59.428 --> 37:02.931
I get why you kept it a secret
for as long as you did, but...

37:04.850 --> 37:07.769
you didn't have to. Not from me.

37:07.769 --> 37:10.772
♪ song continues ♪

37:18.697 --> 37:21.241
The Eye... gives you the knowledge

37:21.241 --> 37:23.243
to get what you want most, right?

37:24.620 --> 37:26.663
- In a way, yeah.

37:27.915 --> 37:29.875
- So, what's it showing you?

37:30.834 --> 37:32.503
- Well, you know.
It's all the Dennis stuff.

37:34.546 --> 37:35.797
- Does that feel right to you?

37:37.299 --> 37:40.344
Finding out what happened
to Dennis is the thing you want

37:40.344 --> 37:42.304
more than anything else?

37:43.847 --> 37:46.850
♪

37:46.850 --> 37:50.395
♪ The wicked drown in water,
let go wicked one ♪

37:51.188 --> 37:54.107
♪ Wicked drown in water ♪

37:55.943 --> 37:59.196
♪ Ah ah-ah ah-ah ♪

38:02.366 --> 38:04.034
♪ River ♪

38:04.034 --> 38:06.954
♪ Ah ah-ah ah-ah ♪

38:10.249 --> 38:12.334
- So, clearly, we got
some stuff to talk about.

38:12.918 --> 38:14.670
I know I should've told you
about the magic,

38:14.670 --> 38:17.172
but, in my defense, it's not
the easiest thing to explain.

38:17.172 --> 38:20.425
I mean, sure, I definitely
knew something was up,

38:20.425 --> 38:22.177
but that was a total curve-ball.

38:22.177 --> 38:25.013
♪ song playing on radio ♪

38:25.013 --> 38:26.682
Also...

38:26.682 --> 38:30.227
I know that's not what's really
bothering you, so I'll just shut up.

38:30.227 --> 38:32.980
- My dad is dating that woman,

38:32.980 --> 38:34.940
Angela, if that's even her real name.

38:34.940 --> 38:37.067
- I'm pretty sure that's her real name--

38:37.067 --> 38:39.278
- Clearly, she's into something shady,

38:39.278 --> 38:41.780
and my dad could be in danger.

38:42.990 --> 38:44.575
We gotta tell him, Chet.

38:46.159 --> 38:49.121
- B, you're a straight shooter,
and I like that.

38:49.121 --> 38:51.832
But what if, and just as a thought,

38:51.832 --> 38:55.544
instead of going right at your dad,
we ease up?

38:56.795 --> 38:59.298
Dig into it quietly. Just in case.

39:00.215 --> 39:02.134
- In case of what?

39:02.134 --> 39:03.844
[sighs]

39:03.844 --> 39:05.804
- In case he's shady, too.

39:05.804 --> 39:08.182
♪

39:08.182 --> 39:11.226
♪ The wicked drown in water,
let the wicked one ♪

39:11.727 --> 39:14.855
♪ Wicked drown in water ♪

39:18.859 --> 39:21.528
- Hey, Trudy?
[sniffs]

39:21.528 --> 39:23.530
- Hey.

39:23.530 --> 39:26.283
Do you need anything? Um, more blankets?

39:26.283 --> 39:28.452
- I'm good. I just wanted...

39:29.077 --> 39:30.495
Are you crying?

39:31.205 --> 39:33.874
- No. No, I'm fine. I just, um...

39:34.833 --> 39:36.084
I'm tired.

39:36.084 --> 39:37.794
♪ song playing on radio ♪

39:37.794 --> 39:39.796
- I didn't mean to be rude before.

39:41.590 --> 39:43.884
I know you're trying to
make me feel at home.

39:43.884 --> 39:46.011
♪

39:47.012 --> 39:48.514
I'm just sad.

39:49.389 --> 39:50.891
I'm scared.

39:52.267 --> 39:54.603
I didn't mean to make you cry.

39:56.104 --> 39:59.316
- I'm a high school guidance counselor.
I can handle little brats.

40:05.531 --> 40:07.533
I'm sad and scared, too.

40:08.575 --> 40:10.619
[sniffling]

40:10.619 --> 40:12.746
You're not the only one
who loves your mom.

40:13.705 --> 40:16.708
♪

40:18.585 --> 40:20.128
♪ River ♪

40:21.380 --> 40:23.882
♪ Ah ah-ah ah-ah ♪

40:26.677 --> 40:28.679
♪ River ♪

40:28.679 --> 40:30.722
[insects chirping]
[clicking]

40:30.722 --> 40:33.976
[radio chatter, static, click]

40:33.976 --> 40:35.227
- JB, come in.

40:35.227 --> 40:38.105
[static]

40:38.647 --> 40:40.941
[click]
JB, this is Joe. Come in.

40:40.941 --> 40:43.360
[static]

40:43.360 --> 40:45.279
[click]
Hey, this was your idea!

40:45.279 --> 40:48.282
Alright? You owe me one. Remember?

40:48.282 --> 40:50.117
You said reach out if I ever need help

40:50.117 --> 40:52.286
from a world-class thief
who looks great in a wig.

40:52.286 --> 40:55.038
Well, I don't care about the wig,
but this is me reaching out.

40:55.038 --> 40:57.332
I'm calling in my favor.
So, you better respond.

40:57.332 --> 40:58.917
You know where to find me. Over.
[click]

40:58.917 --> 41:00.502
[static]

41:00.502 --> 41:03.380
[click]
Find me on the radio. Don't come here.

41:03.380 --> 41:05.924
This needs to stay between us. Over.
[click]

41:05.924 --> 41:08.760
[static]

41:08.760 --> 41:11.180
This is Joe. Over.

41:12.181 --> 41:15.726
Joe Hardy. Over.
[click]

41:15.726 --> 41:18.729
[static]

41:21.607 --> 41:23.275
[slams receiver, tosses paper]

41:23.275 --> 41:26.278
♪

41:26.278 --> 41:27.279
[door shuts]

41:39.833 --> 41:42.002
[ringing, rumbling]

41:42.002 --> 41:44.505
[distorted noises]

41:44.505 --> 41:47.508
[glass tinkling]

41:47.508 --> 41:49.676
♪

41:50.719 --> 41:53.388
[tinkling]
- It's perfect.

41:53.388 --> 41:54.765
[tinkling]

41:54.765 --> 41:57.392
It can hide right here in plain sight.

42:00.354 --> 42:02.356
♪

42:03.148 --> 42:04.358
You again.

42:05.234 --> 42:07.152
Who are you, boy?!

42:07.903 --> 42:09.321
[grunts]

42:11.615 --> 42:13.909
[footsteps]

42:13.909 --> 42:15.410
♪

42:17.329 --> 42:18.872
- You're getting distracted, Frank.

42:19.998 --> 42:21.500
Stay on your path.

42:21.500 --> 42:23.544
Focus on what's in front of you.

42:26.630 --> 42:28.799
- What is it?

42:28.799 --> 42:30.300
What is it for?

42:33.262 --> 42:36.265
[heavy breathing]

42:36.265 --> 42:37.766
♪

42:45.482 --> 42:48.485
♪
